ction explores Balibar’s rethinking of the connections between subjection and subjectivity by tracing the genealogies of these concepts in their discursive history. The 12 essays provide an overview of Balibar’s work after his collaboration with Althusser. They explain and expand his framework; in particular, by restoring Arabic and Islamic thought to the conversation on the citizen subject. The collection includes two previously untranslated essays by Balibar himself on Carl Schmitt and Thomas Hobbes. Key FeaturesThe first English-language edited collection to focus on BalibarPresents and explains Balibar’s key contributions to political theory and the history of political philosophyIncludes two essays by Balibar himself on Carl Schmitt and Thomas Hobbes: 'Schmitt’s Hobbes, Hobbes’s Schmitt' and 'The Mortal God and his Faithful Subjects: Hobbes, Schmitt and the Antinomies of Secularism'Contributors include Étienne Balibar, Nancy Armstrong, Giorgos Fourtounis, Mohamed Moulfi"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalibar, Etienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrutsche, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElsayed, Hanan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aElsayed, Hanan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, James Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFourtounis, Giorgos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesing, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontag, Warren,